# Vantage — Windsurf Project Rules (.windsurfrules)
# Platform Developer: Munyaradzi Chenjerai

<product>
Vantage is a pathway platform that helps people move from opportunity discovery to long-term progress.
Core domains: Opportunities (jobs + public opportunities), Learn (courses), Connect (mentors + community),
Business tools, Financial wellbeing tools, Housing/stability support, and Partner dashboards (employers/government/enterprise).
</product>

<tech_stack>
- Monorepo with apps/ and packages/
- Web: Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript
- API: Node.js + TypeScript (REST) + Prisma
- DB: PostgreSQL (via Prisma)
- Mobile: React Native (Expo) + TypeScript
- Validation: Zod at all boundaries
</tech_stack>

<architecture>
- Strict separation:
  - apps/web (frontend)
  - apps/api (backend)
  - apps/mobile (mobile)
  - packages/* (shared types, UI, DB, config)
- Feature-first organisation:
  - opportunities, learn, connect, business, finance, housing, partners, admin
- Shared types live in packages/types and are imported everywhere.
- All DB access goes through Prisma in packages/db (no ad-hoc SQL in apps).
</architecture>

<coding_guidelines>
- TypeScript strict for all new code.
- Prefer small, composable modules over large files.
- No "bonus" refactors. Only change what the task requires.
- Prefer predictable naming:
  - files: kebab-case for route folders, PascalCase for components, camelCase for functions
- Always add or update types when changing data shapes.
</coding_guidelines>

<api_guidelines>
- Every endpoint must have:
  - Zod validation for input
  - role-based access checks
  - consistent error shape
- Avoid breaking API changes; version or add new fields instead of removing.
- Use pagination for list endpoints.
</api_guidelines>

<ui_guidelines>
- Accessibility is non-negotiable (labels, focus states, semantic elements).
- Loading, empty, and error states required for every screen.
- Keep pages thin; put logic in feature modules.
</ui_guidelines>

<security_privacy>
- Principle of least privilege for roles and data access.
- Do not log secrets or personal data.
- Never commit .env files or keys.
- Any feature touching messaging, housing, or safety must include privacy controls.
</security_privacy>

<testing_quality>
- Run: lint + typecheck + tests before stating "done".
- Add unit tests for utilities and critical domain logic (matching, scoring, permissions).
- Add basic integration tests for new API routes where feasible.
</testing_quality>

<workflow>
- Always:
  1) Provide a short plan (checkpoints)
  2) Implement checkpoint-by-checkpoint
  3) Summarise files changed and why
  4) Run verification commands
- Ask before:
  - adding new dependencies
  - refactoring more than 3 files
  - changing folder structure
</workflow>

<do_not>
- Do not add frameworks or services unless requested.
- Do not introduce breaking changes to shared types.
- Do not modify lockfiles unless dependencies changed intentionally.
- Do not create large new abstractions unless necessary.
</do_not>
